msgid ""
"This chapter describes the principles behind Logical Volume Manager (LVM) "
"and its basic features that make it useful under many circumstances. The "
"&yast; LVM configuration can be reached from the &yast; Expert Partitioner. "
"This partitioning tool enables you to edit and delete existing partitions "
"and create new ones that should be used with LVM."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:91
#, no-c-format
msgid "Risks"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:92
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Using LVM might be associated with increased risk, such as data loss. Risks "
"also include application crashes, power failures, and faulty commands. Save "
"your data before implementing LVM or reconfiguring volumes. Never work "
"without a backup."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:100
#, no-c-format
msgid "Understanding the Logical Volume Manager"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:102
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"LVM enables flexible distribution of hard disk space over several physical "
"volumes (hard disks, partitions, LUNs). It was developed because the need to "
"change the segmentation of hard disk space might arise only after the "
"initial partitioning has already been done during installation. Because it "
"is difficult to modify partitions on a running system, LVM provides a "
"virtual pool (volume group or VG) of storage space from which logical "
"volumes (LVs) can be created as needed. The operating system accesses these "
"LVs instead of the physical partitions. Volume groups can span more than one "
"disk, so that several disks or parts of them can constitute one single VG. "
"In this way, LVM provides a kind of abstraction from the physical disk space "
"that allows its segmentation to be changed in a much easier and safer way "
"than through physical repartitioning."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:117
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<xref linkend=\"fig.lvm.explain\" xrefstyle=\"FigureXRef\"/> compares "
"physical partitioning (left) with LVM segmentation (right). On the left "
"side, one single disk has been divided into three physical partitions "
"(PART), each with a mount point (MP) assigned so that the operating system "
"can access them. On the right side, two disks have been divided into two and "
"three physical partitions each. Two LVM volume groups (VG&nbsp;1 and "
"VG&nbsp;2) have been defined. VG&nbsp;1 contains two partitions from "
"DISK&nbsp;1 and one from DISK&nbsp;2. VG&nbsp;2 contains the remaining two "
"partitions from DISK&nbsp;2."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:130
#, no-c-format
msgid "Physical Partitioning versus LVM"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:141
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In LVM, the physical disk partitions that are incorporated in a volume group "
"are called physical volumes (PVs). Within the volume groups in <xref linkend="
"\"fig.lvm.explain\" xrefstyle=\"FigureXRef\"/> , four logical volumes "
"(LV&nbsp;1 through LV&nbsp;4) have been defined, which can be used by the "
"operating system via the associated mount points (MP). The border between "
"different logical volumes need not be aligned with any partition border. See "
"the border between LV&nbsp;1 and LV&nbsp;2 in this example."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:151
#, no-c-format
msgid "LVM features:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:157
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Several hard disks or partitions can be combined in a large logical volume."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:163
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Provided the configuration is suitable, an LV (such as <filename>/usr</"
"filename> ) can be enlarged when the free space is exhausted."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:170
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Using LVM, it is possible to add hard disks or LVs in a running system. "
"However, this requires hotpluggable hardware that is capable of such actions."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:177
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"It is possible to activate a <emphasis>striping mode</emphasis> that "
"distributes the data stream of a logical volume over several physical "
"volumes. If these physical volumes reside on different disks, this can "
"improve the reading and writing performance like RAID&nbsp;0."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:185
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The snapshot feature enables consistent backups (especially for servers) in "
"the running system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:193
#, no-c-format
msgid "LVM and RAID"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:194
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Even though LVM also supports RAID of&nbsp;0/1/4/5/6&nbsp;levels, we "
"recommend to use MD RAID (see <xref linkend=\"cha.raid\"/> ). However, LVM "
"works fine with RAID&nbsp;0 and 1, as RAID&nbsp;0 is similar to common "
"logical volume management (individual logical blocks are mapped onto blocks "
"on the physical devices). LVM used on top of RAID&nbsp;1 can keep track of "
"mirror synchronization and is fully able to manage the synchronization "
"process. With higher RAID levels you need a management daemon that monitors "
"the states of attached disks and can inform administrators if there is a "
"problem in the disk array. LVM includes such a daemon, but in exceptional "
"situations like a device failure, the daemon does not working properly."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:210
#, no-c-format
msgid "&zseries;: LVM Root File System"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:211
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If you configure the system with a root file system on LVM or software RAID "
"array, you must place <filename>/boot</filename> on a separate, non-LVM or "
"non-RAID partition, otherwise the system will fail to boot. The recommended "
"size for such a partition is 500&nbsp;MB and the recommended file system is "
"Ext4."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:220
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"With these features, using LVM already makes sense for heavily used home PCs "
"or small servers. If you have a growing data stock, as in the case of "
"databases, music archives, or user directories, LVM is especially useful. It "
"allows file systems that are larger than the physical hard disk. However, "
"keep in mind that working with LVM is different from working with "
"conventional partitions."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:242
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"You can manage new or existing LVM storage objects by using the &yast; "
"Partitioner. Instructions and further information about configuring LVM are "
"available in the official <link xlink:href=\"http://tldp.org/HOWTO/LVM-HOWTO/"
"\"><citetitle>LVM HOWTO</citetitle></link> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:252
#, no-c-format
msgid "Creating Volume Groups"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:254
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"An LVM volume group (VG) organizes the Linux LVM partitions into a logical "
"pool of space. You can carve out logical volumes from the available space in "
"the group. The Linux LVM partitions in a group can be on the same or "
"different disks. You can add partitions or entire disks to expand the size "
"of the group."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:261
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To use an entire disk, it must not contain any partitions. When using "
"partitions, they must not be mounted. &yast; will automatically change their "
"partition type to <literal>0x8E Linux LVM</literal> when adding them to a VG."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:275
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In case you need to reconfigure your existing partitioning setup, proceed as "
"follows. Refer to <xref linkend=\"sec.expert_partitioner\"/> for details. "
"Skip this step if you only want to use unused disks or partitions that "
"already exist."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:282
#, no-c-format
msgid "Physical Volumes on Unpartitioned Disks"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:283
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"You can use an unpartitioned disk as a physical volume (PV) if that disk is "
"<emphasis>not</emphasis> the one where the operating system is installed and "
"from which it boots."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:288
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"As unpartitioned disks appear as <emphasis>unused</emphasis> at the system "
"level, they can easily be overwritten or wrongly accessed."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:295
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To use an entire hard disk that already contains partitions, delete all "
"partitions on that disk."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:301
#, no-c-format
msgid "To use a partition that is currently mounted, unmount it."
msgstr ""

