"content of the <guimenu>Options</guimenu> menu depends on the file system. "
"Usually there is no need to change the defaults."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:570
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Under <guimenu>Mounting Options</guimenu> , select <guimenu>Mount partition</"
"guimenu> , then select the mount point. Click <guimenu>Fstab Options</"
"guimenu> to add special mounting options for the volume."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:590
#, no-c-format
msgid "Thinly Provisioned Logical Volumes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:591
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"An LVM logical volume can optionally be thinly provisioned. Thin "
"provisioning allows you to create logical volumes with sizes that overbook "
"the available free space. You create a thin pool that contains unused space "
"reserved for use with an arbitrary number of thin volumes. A thin volume is "
"created as a sparse volume and space is allocated from a thin pool as "
"needed. The thin pool can be expanded dynamically when needed for cost-"
"effective allocation of storage space. Thinly provisioned volumes also "
"support snapshots which can be managed with Snapper&mdash;see <xref linkend="
"\"cha.snapper\"/> for more information."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:602
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To set up a thinly provisioned logical volume, proceed as described in <xref "
"linkend=\"pro.lvm.lv\"/> . When it comes to choosing the volume type, do not "
"choose <guimenu>Normal Volume</guimenu> , but rather <guimenu>Thin Volume</"
"guimenu> or <guimenu>Thin Pool</guimenu> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_lvm.xml:610
#, no-c-format
msgid "<guimenu>Thin pool</guimenu>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:613
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The logical volume is a pool of space that is reserved for use with thin "
"volumes. The thin volumes can allocate their needed space from it on demand."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_lvm.xml:621
#, no-c-format
msgid "<guimenu>Thin volume</guimenu>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:624
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The volume is created as a sparse volume. The volume allocates needed space "
"on demand from a thin pool."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:632
#, no-c-format
msgid "Thinly Provisioned Volumes in a Cluster"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:633
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To use thinly provisioned volumes in a cluster, the thin pool and the thin "
"volumes that use it must be managed in a single cluster resource. This "
"allows the thin volumes and thin pool to always be mounted exclusively on "
"the same node."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:643
#, no-c-format
msgid "Creating Mirrored Volumes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:644
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A logical volume can be created with several mirrors. LVM ensures that data "
"written to an underlying physical volume is mirrored onto a different "
"physical volume. Thus even though a physical volume crashes, you can still "
"access the data on the logical volume. LVM also keeps a log file to manage "
"the synchronization process. The log contains information about which volume "
"regions are currently undergoing synchronization with mirrors. By default "
"the log is stored on disk and if possible on a different disk than are the "
"mirrors. But you may specify a different location for the log, for example "
"volatile memory."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:655
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Currently there are two types of mirror implementation available: \"normal"
"\" (non-raid) <literal>mirror</literal> logical volumes and <literal>raid1</"
"literal> logical volumes."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:660
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"After you create mirrored logical volumes, you can perform standard "
"operations with mirrored logical volumes like activating, extending, and "
"removing."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:666
#, no-c-format
msgid "Setting Up Mirrored Non-raid Logical Volumes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:667
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To create a mirrored volume use the <command>lvcreate</command> command. The "
"following example creates a 500 GB logical volume with two mirrors called "
"<emphasis>lv1</emphasis> which uses a volume group <emphasis>vg1</emphasis> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_lvm.xml:673
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;lvcreate -L 500G -m 2 -n lv1 vg1"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:674
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Such a logical volume is a linear volume (without striping) that provides "
"three copies of the file system. The <literal>m</literal> option specifies "
"the count of mirrors. The <literal>L</literal> option specifies the size of "
"the logical volumes."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:680
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The logical volume is divided into regions of the 512 KB default size. If "
"you need a different size of regions, use the <literal>-R</literal> option "
"followed by the desired region size in megabytes. Or you can configure the "
"preferred region size by editing the <literal>mirror_region_size</literal> "
"option in the <filename>lvm.conf</filename> file."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:689
#, no-c-format
msgid "Setting Up <literal>raid1</literal> Logical Volumes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:690
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"As LVM supports RAID you can implement mirroring by using RAID1. Such "
"implementation provides the following advantages compared to the non-raid "
"mirrors:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:697
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"LVM maintains a fully redundant bitmap area for each mirror image, which "
"increases its fault handling capabilities."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:703
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Mirror images can be temporarily split from the array and then merged back."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:709
#, no-c-format
msgid "The array can handle transient failures."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:714
#, no-c-format
msgid "The LVM RAID 1 implementation supports snapshots."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:719
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"On the other hand, this type of mirroring implementation does not enable to "
"create a logical volume in a clustered volume group."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:723
#, no-c-format
msgid "To create a mirror volume by using RAID, issue the command"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_lvm.xml:726
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;lvcreate --type raid1 -m 1 -L 1G -n lv1 vg1"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:727
#, no-c-format
msgid "where the options/parameters have the following meanings:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:732
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>--type</literal> - you need to specify <literal>raid1</literal> , "
"otherwise the command uses the implicit segment type <literal>mirror</"
"literal> and creates a non-raid mirror."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:739
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>-m</literal> - specifies the count of mirrors."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:744
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>-L</literal> - specifies the size of the logical volume."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:749
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>-n</literal> - by using this option you specify a name of the "
"logical volume."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:755
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>vg1</literal> - is a name of the volume group used by the logical "
"volume."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:761
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"LVM creates a logical volume of one extent size for each data volume in the "
"array. If you have two mirrored volumes, LVM creates another two volumes "
"that stores metadata."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:766
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"After you create a RAID logical volume, you can use the volume in the same "
"way as a common logical volume. You can activate it, extend it, etc."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
