#: storage_lvm.xml:1503
#, no-c-format
msgid "Resizing a Logical Volume with Commands"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1504
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <command>lvresize</command> , <command>lvextend</command> , and "
"<command>lvreduce</command> commands are used to resize logical volumes. See "
"the man pages for each of these commands for syntax and options information. "
"To extend an LV there must be enough unallocated space available on the VG."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1511
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The recommended way to grow or shrink a logical volume is to use the &yast; "
"Partitioner. When using &yast;, the size of the file system in the volume "
"will automatically be adjusted, too."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1516
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"LVs can be extended or shrunk manually while they are being used, but this "
"may not be true for a file system on them. Extending or shrinking the LV "
"does not automatically modify the size of file systems in the volume. You "
"must use a different command to grow the file system afterward. For "
"information about resizing file systems, see <xref linkend=\"cha.resize_fs\" "
"xrefstyle=\"ChapTitleOnPage\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1524
#, no-c-format
msgid "Ensure that you use the right sequence when manually resizing an LV:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1529
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If you extend an LV, you must extend the LV before you attempt to grow the "
"file system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1535
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If you shrink an LV, you must shrink the file system before you attempt to "
"shrink the LV."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1541
#, no-c-format
msgid "To extend the size of a logical volume:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1551
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If the logical volume contains an Ext2 or Ext4 file system, which do not "
"support online growing, dismount it. In case it contains file systems that "
"are hosted for a virtual machine (such as a &xen; VM), shut down the VM "
"first."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1559
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"At the terminal console prompt, enter the following command to grow the size "
"of the logical volume:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_lvm.xml:1563
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.sudo;lvextend -L +<replaceable>SIZE</replaceable> /dev/"
"<replaceable>VG_NAME</replaceable>/<replaceable>LV_NAME</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1564
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For <replaceable>SIZE</replaceable> , specify the amount of space you want "
"to add to the logical volume, such as 10 GB. Replace <filename>/dev/"
"<replaceable>VG_NAME</replaceable>/<replaceable>LV_NAME</replaceable></"
"filename> with the Linux path to the logical volume, such as <filename>/dev/"
"LOCAL/DATA</filename> . For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_lvm.xml:1571
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;lvextend -L +10GB /dev/vg1/v1<replaceable/>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1580
#, no-c-format
msgid "In case you have dismounted the file system, mount it again."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1585
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For example, to extend an LV with a (mounted and active) Btrfs on it by 10 "
"GB:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_lvm.xml:1589
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.sudo;lvextend −L +10G /dev/LOCAL/DATA\n"
"&prompt.sudo;btrfs filesystem resize +10G /dev/LOCAL/DATA"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1591
#, no-c-format
msgid "To shrink the size of a logical volume:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1601
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If the logical volume does not contain a Btrfs file system, dismount it. In "
"case it contains file systems that are hosted for a virtual machine (such as "
"a &xen; VM), shut down the VM first. Note that volumes with the XFS file "
"system cannot be reduced in size."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1609
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Adjust the size of the file system. See <xref linkend=\"cha.resize_fs\"/> "
"for details."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1615
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"At the terminal console prompt, enter the following command to shrink the "
"size of the logical volume to the size of the file system:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_lvm.xml:1619
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.sudo;lvreduce /dev/<replaceable>VG_NAME</replaceable>/"
"<replaceable>LV_NAME</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1622
#, no-c-format
msgid "In case you have unmounted the file system, mount it again."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1627
#, no-c-format
msgid "For example, to shrink an LV with a Btrfs on it by 5 GB:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_lvm.xml:1630
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.sudo;btrfs filesystem resize -size 5G /dev/LOCAL/DATA\n"
"sudo lvreduce /dev/LOCAL/DATA"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:1633
#, no-c-format
msgid "Resizing the Volume and the File System with a Single Command"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1636
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Starting with &productname; 12 SP1, <command>lvextend</command> , "
"<command>lvresize</command> , and <command>lvreduce</command> support the "
"option <option>--resizefs</option> which will not only change the size of "
"the volume, but will also resize the file system. Therefore the examples for "
"<command>lvextend</command> and <command>lvreduce</command> shown above can "
"alternatively be run as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_lvm.xml:1644
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.sudo;lvextend --resizefs −L +10G /dev/LOCAL/DATA\n"
"&prompt.sudo;lvreduce  --resizefs -L -5G /dev/LOCAL/DATA"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1646
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Note that the <option>--resizefs</option> is supported for the following "
"file systems: ext2/3/4, Btrfs, XFS. Resizing Btrfs with this option is "
"currently only available on &productname;, since it is not yet accepted "
"upstream."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:1656
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Dynamic Aggregation of LVM Metadata via <systemitem class=\"daemon"
"\">lvmetad</systemitem>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1657
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Most LVM commands require an accurate view of the LVM metadata stored on the "
"disk devices in the system. With the current LVM design, if this information "
"is not available, LVM must scan all the physical disk devices in the system. "
"This requires a significant amount of I/O operations in systems that have "
"many disks. In case a disk fails to respond, LVM commands might run into a "
"timeout while waiting for the disk."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1665
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Dynamic aggregation of LVM metadata via <systemitem class=\"daemon"
"\">lvmetad</systemitem> provides a solution for this problem. The purpose of "
"the <systemitem class=\"daemon\">lvmetad</systemitem> daemon is to eliminate "
"the need for this scanning by dynamically aggregating metadata information "
"each time the status of a device changes. These events are signaled to "
"<systemitem class=\"daemon\">lvmetad</systemitem> by udev rules. If the "
"daemon is not running, LVM performs a scan as it normally would do."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1675
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This feature is enabled by default. In case it is disabled on your system, "
"proceed as follows to enable it:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1681
#, no-c-format
msgid "Open a terminal console."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1686
#, no-c-format
msgid "Stop the <systemitem class=\"daemon\">lvmetad</systemitem> daemon:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_lvm.xml:1689
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;systemctl stop lvm2-lvmetad"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1692
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Edit <filename>/etc/lvm/lvm.conf</filename> and set <literal>use_lvmetad</"
"literal> to <literal>1</literal> :"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_lvm.xml:1696
#, no-c-format
msgid "use_lvmetad = 1"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1699
#, no-c-format
msgid "Restart the <systemitem class=\"daemon\">lvmetad</systemitem> daemon:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_lvm.xml:1702
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;systemctl start lvm2-lvmetad"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:1708
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using LVM Cache Volumes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1709
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"LVM supports the use of fast block devices (such as an SSD device) as write-"
"back or write-through caches for large slower block devices. The cache "
"logical volume type uses a small and fast LV to improve the performance of a "
"large and slow LV."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1715
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To set up LVM caching, you need to create two logical volumes on the caching "
"device. A large one is used for the caching itself, a smaller volume is used "
"to store the caching metadata. These two volumes need to be part of the same "
"volume group as the original volume. When these volumes are created, they "
"need to be converted into a cache pool which needs to be attached to the "
"original volume:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:1724
#, no-c-format
msgid "Setting up a Cached Logical Volume"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1726
#, no-c-format
msgid "Create the original volume (on a slow device) if not already existing."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1731
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Add the physical volume (from a fast device) to the same volume group the "
"original volume is part of and create the cache data volume on the physical "
"volume."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1738
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Create the cache metadata volume. The size should be 1/1000 of the size of "
"the cache data volume, with a minimum size of 8 MB."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1744
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Combine the cache data volume and metadata volume into a cache pool volume:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_lvm.xml:1748
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.sudo;lvconvert --type cache-pool --poolmetadata "
"<replaceable>VOLUME_GROUP/METADATA_VOLUME</replaceable> "
"<replaceable>VOLUME_GROUP/CACHING_VOLUME</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1751
#, no-c-format
msgid "Attach the cache pool to the original volume:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_lvm.xml:1754
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.sudo;lvconvert --type cache --cachepool <replaceable>VOLUME_GROUP/"
"CACHING_VOLUME</replaceable> <replaceable>VOLUME_GROUP/ORIGINAL_VOLUME</"
"replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1757
#, no-c-format
msgid "For more information on LVM caching, see the lvmcache(7) man page."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:1763
#, no-c-format
msgid "Tagging LVM2 Storage Objects"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1765
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A tag is an unordered keyword or term assigned to the metadata of a storage "
"object. Tagging allows you to classify collections of LVM storage objects in "
"ways that you find useful by attaching an unordered list of tags to their "
"metadata."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:1773
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using LVM2 Tags"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1774
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"After you tag the LVM2 storage objects, you can use the tags in commands to "
"accomplish the following tasks:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1780
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Select LVM objects for processing according to the presence or absence of "
"specific tags."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1786
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Use tags in the configuration file to control which volume groups and "
"logical volumes are activated on a server."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1792
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Override settings in a global configuration file by specifying tags in the "
"command."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1798
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A tag can be used in place of any command line LVM object reference that "
"accepts:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1804
#, no-c-format
msgid "a list of objects"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1809
#, no-c-format
msgid "a single object as long as the tag expands to a single object"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1814
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Replacing the object name with a tag is not supported everywhere yet. After "
"the arguments are expanded, duplicate arguments in a list are resolved by "
"removing the duplicate arguments, and retaining the first instance of each "
"argument."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1820
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Wherever there might be ambiguity of argument type, you must prefix a tag "
"with the commercial at sign (@) character, such as <literal>@mytag</"
"literal> . Elsewhere, using the <quote>@</quote> prefix is optional."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_lvm.xml:1829
#, no-c-format
msgid "Requirements for Creating LVM2 Tags"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1830
#, no-c-format
msgid "Consider the following requirements when using tags with LVM:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_lvm.xml:1835
#, no-c-format
msgid "Supported Characters"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1837
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"An LVM tag word can contain the ASCII uppercase characters A to Z, lowercase "
"characters a to z, numbers 0 to 9, underscore (_), plus (+), hyphen (-), and "
"period (.). The word cannot begin with a hyphen. The maximum length is 128 "
"characters."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_lvm.xml:1846
#, no-c-format
msgid "Supported Storage Objects"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1848
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"You can tag LVM2 physical volumes, volume groups, logical volumes, and "
"logical volume segments. PV tags are stored in its volume group’s metadata. "
"Deleting a volume group also deletes the tags in the orphaned physical "
"volume. Snapshots cannot be tagged, but their origin can be tagged."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_lvm.xml:1855
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"LVM1 objects cannot be tagged because the disk format does not support it."
